<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-343-212  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 343 212.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 12 1989 v8 n12 p138(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Used computers on GSA schedule may cause delay. (US GeneralServices Administration) (Fedwatch) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dornan, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppealsUsed EquipmentComputersGovernment ContractsData ProcessingGovernment Regulation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Federal developments and documents. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Used Computers On GSA Schedule May Cause DelayandM;The General Services Administration Board of Contract Appeals decision 9965-Pof May 11 will have a profound effect on the GSA automated data processingschedule program.andM;This ruling will force GSA, for the first time, to allow used computers to beplaced on the GSA schedule.andM;It also prohibits any agency from using any fiscal 1990 schedule contractuntil GSA gives the used equipment community the opportunity to obtainschedule contracts.andM;This could seriously delay vendors' negotiations with GSA, and it may evenprohibit any new orders under 1990 contracts until well into the new fiscalyear.andM;The decision also may significantly change the nature of the entire scheduleprogram.andP;  IBM Corp. and Digital Equipment Corp. dominate the schedule marketwith 34 percent and 19 percent respectively of the total fiscal 1988 ADPschedule sales of $1.9 billion.andM;More ChoicesandM;Agencies wishing to order equipment from either of these companies using theGSA schedule now must evaluate identical or equivalent used equipment fromthe used equipment schedule contractors.andM;Since used equipment is almost always cheaper than new equipment, it will bevery difficult, but not impossible [see FIRMR 201-32.206(h)], for agencies tojustify ordering more expensive equipment from IBM or Digital.andP;  This couldlower IBM and Digital sales in the federal market since both companies get asubstantial amount of their direct revenue from schedule sales.andM;This ruling affects only the GSA schedule program.andP;  It does not preventagencies from requiring only new equipment in solicitations where there is agood justification.andM;Agencies could allow used equipment to be offered and include in theselection process an evaluation of the &quot;currentness&quot; of the proposedequipment's technology as provided for in FIRMR 201-32.203(h).andO;</TEXT></DOC>